The second scenario of anti-counterfeiting application is to have a piece of blank cellulose paper and a bottle of PMTS/PSMA PNP ink at hand, and then we also envisioned two modes of operation. The first mode is to write the letter “Y” on the cellulose paper with a brush dip-coated with PMTS/PSMA PNP ink in advance. The letter was barely visible in natural light before UV light irradiation ( Figure S16
). However, after UV light irradiation (365 nm, 60 W), the fluorescence of the written letters is clearly visible and the fluorescence color dynamically changes from blue to light violet and finally to bright red, as in Fig. 8
a. The second mode is to inject PMTS/PSMA PNP ink into a commercially available but empty fountain pen and then writing “SOOCHOW” on cellulose paper (Fig. 8 b). The photochromic effect is consistent with the letter “Y” in the second scenario.

The anti-counterfeiting applications employing PMTS PNP ink for writing “W” on blank cellulose paper with a brush were also carried out (
                           Figure S18
                        ). Compared with PMTS/PSMA PNP ink, PMTS PNP ink obtains a similar dynamic photochromic effect, but the fluorescence intensity is relatively weaker. This is consistent with the results of the previous photophysical study that PMTS/PSMA PNPs fluorescence in colloidal solution is stronger than PMTS PNPs.
